<h1>Problem 927 - 2003 IMOSL, G4, G</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(\Gamma_1\), \(\Gamma_2\), \(\Gamma_3\), \(\Gamma_4\) be distinct circles such that \(\Gamma_1\), \(\Gamma_3\) are externally tangent at \(P\), and \(\Gamma_2\), \(\Gamma_4\) are externally tangent at the same point \(P\). Suppose that \(\Gamma_1\) and \(\Gamma_2\); \(\Gamma_2\) and \(\Gamma_3\); \(\Gamma_3\) and \(\Gamma_4\); \(\Gamma_4\) and \(\Gamma_1\) meet at \(A\), \(B\), \(C\), \(D\), respectively, and that all these points are different from \(P\). Prove that</p>
<p>\[\frac{AB\cdot BC}{AD\cdot DC}=\frac{PB^2}{PD^2}.\]</p>
